Actually that is totally inaccurate, and if its the basis for your argument, I'd reread the original post. The poster is not complaining about people &quot;wigging&quot; or &quot;going off&quot; on someone's grammer in an agressive manner as you described above. The original poster is chastizing ANYONE that points out, politely or otherwise, a mistake in his grammar. Obviously, if someone were to disrespect me while correcting my grammar, I'd have a problem with him or her, but because of the disrespectful tone, not the correction. <br>
<br>
[I am never against self improvement. Let's be serious though. Self improvement comes from within. If you want to argue that, fine. My next point then is simple: Why would anyone in their right minds, especially me, want pointers on how to be a &quot;better person&quot; from the morons that frequent this message board? Ego check = over the top. Yes. Look around. I wanna take improvement advice from THESE people? Give me a break. That would be like taking a sensitivity class taught by Saddam Hussein. Hey, maybe I can sign up for that NASCAR driver's training course taught by Hellen Keller!!!]<br>
<br>
When I mentioned self improvement it was in the context of acknowledging a grammar mistake and learning. I wouldn't expect you to take advice on your lovelife or your career from people here, but certainly plenty of people here are qualified to point out spelling errors. <br>
<br>
[Yea, yer all right. It's just me really. See, if I see someone type: &quot;pst, needing help. if u can assist me i would be gr8tly appresiating it&quot;, I would say to myself &quot;ok, this guy is asking for anyone that can help him to send him a tell and he would be grateful&quot;. If I feel like helping him, I will. If I don't, I won't. If he's a nice person, chances are I will.]<br>
<br>
Now you're talking about in-game chat, which is another story entirely. Many times I will use abbreviations etc to get the point across with as little text as possible, because in game you are often multitasking and efficiency is important. I've never been corrected on something I've said in game, the thought of it seems absurd to me. Although at the same time I don't find myself saying stupid @#%$ that you hear in ooc and auc all the time. /shrug<br>
<br>
On a message board its another story though, where you have all the time in the world to gather your thoughts and post coherant ideas. <br>
<br>
[Then some of you prissy little f.uckdongs on a stick are saying: &quot;if they use PST or if they can't even spell it out I don't care if they are Mother Theresa's ghost I will flat out tell them that I will not help them.&quot; &lt;folds arms, stands stiff, nose in air&gt;]<br>
<br>
/shrug know that in life and even in Everquest people will judge you based on your ability or in some peoples' cases, effort, to communicate. Better to learn it via EQ than the hard way, unemployment.<br>
<br>
[Get a grip. These people know where to go for their &quot;self improvement&quot;. If they want it, they'll ask for it. Some of the non-native english speakers ask for it, good for them. Help em out.]<br>
<br>
You're absolutely right, they are entitled to take as much or as little care in their posts as they want. And critics have an equal entitlement to point out their slothfulness.<br>
